      "side": 1,
      "message": "Line 100: 🔴 The `snprintf` format specifier `%012llx` expects `unsigned long long`, but the mask `0xffffffffffffULL` produces a 48-bit value which is fine in practice. However, the fields extracted from `a` and `b` don\u0027t correctly produce a valid RFC 4122 v4 UUID. The version nibble (bits 12–15 of `time_hi_and_version`) should appear in the third group, and the variant bits (bits 6–7 of `clock_seq_hi`) in the fourth group. Currently:\n- The version bits are set on `a` at bits 12–15 (`a \u0026 0xffffffffffff0fff | 0x4000`), which is correct for the third group only if the third group is `a \u0026 0xffff`. That checks out.\n- The variant is set on `b` bits 62–63 (`b \u0026 0x3fff... | 0x8000...`), and the fourth group extracts `(b \u003e\u003e 48) \u0026 0xffff` — that\u0027s bits 48–63 of `b`, so bits 62–63 carry the variant. This is correct.\n\nHowever, the format string uses `%012llx` for the last 48 bits which is correct. The real issue: the cast `static_cast\u003cunsigned\u003e` for 32-bit and 16-bit fields is fine on all platforms, but `static_cast\u003cunsigned long long\u003e` for the last field is only needed because of `%llx`. Consider using `PRIx64`/`PRIx32` from `\u003ccinttypes\u003e` for portability, or simply use `fmt::format` / `std::format` consistent with the rest of the codebase.",
      "revId": "3662bf671fe456bafeed1c1f2bd8eb3335f9487f",
      "serverId": "1e26b4c1-6b8c-47ff-9df7-501b633d3b5a"
