      "writtenOn": "2026-05-13T19:05:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Line 157: 🔴 The `pre-\u003etcpReady` flag is checked under `pre-\u003em` in `setOnRecv`, but `async_write` is called while still holding the lock. `async_write` may complete synchronously (or inline on some ASIO implementations), which could re-enter the callback and attempt to lock `pre-\u003em` again (though unlikely with current flow). More importantly, holding a mutex while calling into ASIO\u0027s write path can cause priority inversion and latency spikes. Move the `async_write` call outside the lock:\n\n```suggestion\n    channel-\u003esetOnRecv([pre, channelKeep](const uint8_t* data, size_t size) -\u003e ssize_t {\n        bool ready;\n        {\n            std::lock_guard lk(pre-\u003em);\n            ready \u003d pre-\u003etcpReady;\n            if (!ready) {\n                pre-\u003ebytes.insert(pre-\u003ebytes.end(), data, data + size);\n                return static_cast\u003cssize_t\u003e(size);\n            }\n        }\n        auto buf \u003d std::make_shared\u003cstd::vector\u003cuint8_t\u003e\u003e(data, data + size);\n        asio::async_write(*pre-\u003etcp,\n                          asio::buffer(*buf),\n                          [buf](const std::error_code\u0026 ec, std::size_t) {\n                              if (ec)\n                                  JAMI_DEBUG(\"[SvcTunnel] write to TCP failed: {}\",\n                                             ec.message());\n                          });\n        return static_cast\u003cssize_t\u003e(size);\n    });\n```",
      "revId": "3662bf671fe456bafeed1c1f2bd8eb3335f9487f",
      "serverId": "1e26b4c1-6b8c-47ff-9df7-501b633d3b5a"
