      "side": 1,
      "message": "[critical] Line 233: 🔴 `relayTcpToChannel` captures `reader` (a `shared_ptr\u003cfunction\u003e`) inside the lambda stored in `*reader`, creating a strong reference cycle: `reader -\u003e lambda -\u003e reader`. This cycle is never broken because the only cleanup path (`channelKeep-\u003eshutdown()` / `tcpKeep-\u003eclose()`) does not reset `*reader`. The `std::function` and its captures (including `channelKeep`, `tcpKeep`, `buf`) will leak.\n\nBreak the cycle by using a `weak_ptr` or by explicitly clearing `*reader` on shutdown:\n\n```suggestion\n    *reader \u003d [channelKeep, tcpKeep, buf, reader]() {\n        tcpKeep-\u003easync_read_some(asio::buffer(*buf),\n                                 [channelKeep, tcpKeep, buf, reader](const std::error_code\u0026 ec,\n                                                                     std::size_t n) {\n            if (ec || n \u003d\u003d 0) {\n                channelKeep-\u003eshutdown();\n                std::error_code ig;\n                tcpKeep-\u003eclose(ig);\n                *reader \u003d nullptr;  // break the cycle\n                return;\n            }\n            std::error_code wec;\n            channelKeep-\u003ewrite(buf-\u003edata(), n, wec);\n            if (wec) {\n                channelKeep-\u003eshutdown();\n                std::error_code ig;\n                tcpKeep-\u003eclose(ig);\n                *reader \u003d nullptr;  // break the cycle\n                return;\n            }\n            (*reader)();\n        });\n    };\n```",
      "revId": "3662bf671fe456bafeed1c1f2bd8eb3335f9487f",
